title: pokemon partner requests!
body:
hey tumblr! i’m fi - nice to meet you all! ♡

my friend @pokepartners​ has a blog on here for pokemon partner / team requests, and i thought it looked like a really cool idea - so i’ve decided to have a go myself! i’m completely new to this, but i’ve always loved pokemon, and i think it’d be a really neat thing to do.

if anyone’s interested, please check out my ‘how to request’ page - and then submit your requests here! if anyone has any questions, feel free to ask me anything you want here - or shoot me a message!

as a side-note, i also like doing headcanons, worldbuilding and other pokemon-related things, as well as writing fanfics, so if anyone wants to discuss any of those things, i’d love to do that too! ♡

reblogs would be appreciated

- fi xoxo

body:
So, I’ve been really slacking in the writing department, and need a boost! On top of that, I need funds to help me deal with daily college life. So I’m doing a writing commission sale!

Basic rules:

  • $5 for 1000-1250 words
  • Must be paid through paypal
  • No OCs, sorry
  • Will write for:
    • Transformers (any continuity)
    • Bionicle
    • Pokemon
    • DC Comics
    • Titanfall
    • RWBY
    • Mega Man
  • Must be open for DMs if commissioning NSFW content

Even if you can’t get a commission, a reblog of this would be appreciated!

summary: mental health issues similar to that found in humans is not uncommon in Pokemon. It is generally treated the same way, however,...
body:
mental health issues similar to that found in humans is not uncommon in Pokemon. It is generally treated the same way, however, it is not always found. 

Depression in Pokemon is usually caused by traumatic events, mistreatment, or a general mental issue.
Anxiety in Pokemon is usually caused by being separated from other Pokemon for extended periods of time, or in any similar way having them be antisocial.

blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.

blog.name: inikavulpixelreviews
blog.title: Let's Talk About Pokemon!
blog.description:
Reviewing my personal opinion on every single Pokemon! Yes, all 809 of them!
(Mostly) Daily Uploads, 3 PM EST.

summary: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Bunnelby and Diggersby
title: Let’s Talk About Pokemon - Bunnelby and Diggersby
body:
659: Bunnelby

Admittedly, Bunnelby is a Pokemon I’ll readily forget about most of the time. And I’ll probably just as quickly forget about it shortly after writing and posting this review. But y'know what? Bunnelby’s a cute rabbit Pokemon. Cuter than even Buneary.  It has a much more rabbit-like face with an adorably goofy look on its mug. I guess it’s only a shame I’m not so fond on the color scheme that’s both muddy and muted at the same time. Obviously it makes sense given it’ll pick up the Ground type upon evolving, but I’m just not a fan of it. These starting early-game Pokes end up looking pretty drab, but I guess they’re just inherently gonna be more grounded designs.

Personal Score: 6.5/10

Definitely not an Easter bunny, but a good bunny!

660: Diggersby

Diggersby ends up going in the polar opposite direction of Lopunny, more what you’d expect out of a rabbit Pokemon and becoming fat and fluffy. And also poised like a construction worker, even having a 5-o-clock shadow and big arms shaped like excavator arms. Even to a point where they’re patterned like they’re caked in dirt and mud. Which is a fun way to go about incorporating bunny behavior in making burrows in the ground.

Personal Score: 7/10

One of the better second-stages to these common early-game woodland critters. Even if, again, I forget about it a lot. I’m glad with Watchog-onwards at least the obligatory Normal type rodent get a slightly interesting second-stage.

Overall:

It feels so strange that these are this forgettable to me. When I recall them, I think “huh, that’s right. These are some fun, underrated Pokemon designs.” But then I’ll forget about them again. I’d chalk it up to this being the 6th generation in a row to feature the common woodland animal thing, so maybe that aspect of Pokemon itself is getting predictable and stale. But I can passively think of Gumshoos just fine. Hmmm.

I could just chalk it up to say Diggersby just feels a little mundane compared to how fun most of the rest of Gen 6 is.

[Archive]

Which is a fun way to go about incorporating bunny behavior in making burrows in the ground.

Personal Score: 7/10

One of the better second-stages to these common early-game woodland critters. Even if, again, I forget about it a lot. I’m glad with Watchog-onwards at least the obligatory Normal type rodent get a slightly interesting second-stage.

Overall:

It feels so strange that these are this forgettable to me. When I recall them, I think “huh, that’s right. These are some fun, underrated Pokemon designs.” But then I’ll forget about them again. I’d chalk it up to this being the 6th generation in a row to feature the common woodland animal thing, so maybe that aspect of Pokemon itself is getting predictable and stale. But I can passively think of Gumshoos just fine. Hmmm.

I could just chalk it up to say Diggersby just feels a little mundane compared to how fun most of the rest of Gen 6 is.

659: Bunnelby

Admittedly, Bunnelby is a Pokemon I’ll readily forget about most of the time. And I’ll probably just as quickly forget about it shortly after writing and posting this review. But y'know what? Bunnelby’s a cute rabbit Pokemon. Cuter than even Buneary.  It has a much more rabbit-like face with an adorably goofy look on its mug. I guess it’s only a shame I’m not so fond on the color scheme that’s both muddy and muted at the same time. Obviously it makes sense given it’ll pick up the Ground type upon evolving, but I’m just not a fan of it. These starting early-game Pokes end up looking pretty drab, but I guess they’re just inherently gonna be more grounded designs.

summary: Inktober Day 2- Tranquil Pillump- Sandbag Pokémon Type- Normal/Ground Ability- Sand Force/Filter (Hidden) Pillump feed on sand,...
caption:
Inktober Day 2- Tranquil

Pillump- Sandbag Pokémon

Type- Normal/Ground

Ability- Sand Force/Filter (Hidden)

Pillump feed on sand, filling their hollow bodies up to become big and sturdy. Despite their small size, they’re very heavy- Trainers sometimes injure themselves trying to lift up their Pillump. Rarely, they may accidentally consume a Sandygast when feeding. When this happens, they become aggressive and irritable, a stark change from their typical placid disposition, until the Sandygast manages to escape.

Napsack- Sandbag Pokémon

Type- Normal/Ground

Ability- Sand Force/Filter (Hidden)

Evolves from Pillump at level 39.

Napsack are calm, peaceful Pokémon that spend most of their time asleep. They are always surrounded by young Pillump, who will climb on top of the adult to sleep, creating an impenetrable barrier that lasts until the Napsack awakens and moves. This can sometimes be a problem, as there have been multiple cases of a Napsack falling asleep right in the middle of a route…
